Ideological systems can be represented within a four-dimensional space
defined by the continuation primitives:

• Identity
• Structure
• Coordination
• Capacity

Different systems occupy different positions within this space,
resulting in varying levels of cooperation intensity, stability,
and verification capability.

The viability of a system depends on whether its configuration
supports continuation under the required level of coordination.

What are commonly referred to as ideologies are not singular systems,
but composites of multiple trust configurations across different domains,
including economic, political, institutional, and cultural layers.

Each domain operates with its own structure of identity, governance,
coordination, and capacity, and the overall behaviour of a society
emerges from the interaction of these layered systems.

